My research and analysis say that a few ingredients work better than the others when it comes to hyperpigmentation. If you are tired of dealing with dark spots and pigmentation, then these are the ingredients you need to include in your skincare routine for fabulous results.👇🏻

🪄Kojic acid: This ingredient inhibits tyrosinase enzymes, a skin lightening agent that keeps melanin under control, which naturally reduces hyperpigmentation. It works well when used with arbutin and citric acid.

🪄Vitamin C: A highly-loved skincare ingredient, vitamin C prevents melanin production and creates a barrier on the skin against pollution and UV rays. Also known as ascorbic acid, vitamin C eliminates free radicals that might damage the skin and reduce the chances of more dark spots.

🪄Mandelic acid:  An effective alpha-hydroxy-acid, mandelic acid works wonders on post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation. It serves as the perfect exfoliant for sensitive skin that removes all dead skin cells and improves cell turnover, leaving behind a brighter complexion.

🪄Azelaic acid:  Hormonal pigmentation (melasma) can be difficult to treat, especially in pregnant women. But since azelaic acid is gentler as compared to its counterparts, it is allowed in pregnancy too. It gently reduces breakouts and acne and balances bacteria on the skin while handling discolouration.

🪄Niacinamide: This powerhouse ingredient helps keep acne at bay, thus naturally reducing acne scars and pigmentation on the skin. It is a natural pigment corrector that is safe for sensitive skin as well. 

You can use topical creams infused with such ingredients for desired results. Consult your doctor for treatment options.

It’s UV Awareness Month! What do I recommend and practice for safe protection from UV rays? Find out, here!

Here are a few sunscreen tips I follow for overall protection from UV rays. 🌞

😎 Always pick a sunscreen with SPF 30 and higher
😎 Reapply when needed. If you are heading to the beach or will be directly under the sun, reapply every 2 hours
😎 Slather on sunscreen liberally
😎 Use it on all exposed parts of the body, not just the face
😎 Cover up with long sleeves and hats for minimal UV damage

Let me know in the comments which of these you already follow and do share if you have some fun suncare tips of your own.

One wrong step—and your summer skincare can do more harm than good.

➡️ I see this every year: breakouts, pigmentation, and sensitivity caused by the wrong routines.

Let me set the record straight.

Stop doing this:
✖️ Splashing cold water all day
✖️ Rubbing raw ice directly
✖️ Skipping moisturiser in the heat
✖️ Using sunscreen only on holidays
✖️ Bleaching to “remove tan”

Start doing this instead:
✔️ Cleanse twice a day with a gentle face wash
✔️ Use a cooling mist—not constant water
✔️ Wrap your ice cube or use a jade roller
✔️ Hydrate with a light, water-based moisturiser
✔️ Apply sunscreen every single day—even indoors
✔️ Use actives like niacinamide or lactic acid for tanning—not bleach

❓Which of these mistakes have you been guilty of? Comment below!

Disclaimer: This content is for informational purposes only and not a substitute for professional medical advice.

Dr Geetika Mittal Gupta, skin expert, summer care, skincare mistakes, Indian heat

You’ve prepped, you’ve swam—but don’t skip the POST-CARE!👇🏻

This is where real damage control begins. Here’s what I recommend post-swim:

✔️ Clarifying shampoo to rinse out chlorine, salt, and sweat buildup
✔️ Protein-rich hair mask to strengthen and restore elasticity
✔️ Omega-rich serums or oils to lock in moisture and smooth the cuticle
✔️ Gently cleanse hairline & nape with salicylic acid—commonly missed, but breakout-prone
✔️ No heat styling — your hair’s already been through enough

Tag your water-loving friend who always forgets this part!

If Alia Bhatt can confidently walk the red carpet flaunting her freckles—why should you hide yours? 🌟

Other celebs like Meghan Markle, Emma Stone, and Lindsay Lohan have all embraced their natural freckles in the spotlight.

Freckles are harmless skin features, not damage. They can deepen with sun exposure, so protecting your skin is essential.

Skincare ingredients like Vitamin C, niacinamide, and licorice extract can help prevent further pigmentation, while treatments such as microneedling, lasers, and chemical peels offer safe options to reduce freckles if desired.

Whether you choose to keep them or reduce them, the priority is always skin health and smart care.
